1
00:00:04,198 --> 00:00:28,856
Foundation Course 2, Talk 4 Right Intention Right Intention is the second step on the Noble Eightfold Path and it is the crucial link between Right Understanding and the translation of that Right Understanding into the virtuous conduct of Right Action, Speech and Livelihood and the development of the meditative life through Right Effort, Awareness and Concentration.

2
00:00:29,596 --> 00:00:38,587
What the Buddha has shown is that by developing right intention we can spiral away from the crippling and anguishing syndromes of pleasure pain and guilt.

3
00:00:40,929 --> 00:00:47,118
Right understanding of the Four Noble Truths and the Lord of Karma clears the mind of ignorance.

4
00:00:47,999 --> 00:00:51,904
Ignorance is the base root cause of all our unskillful actions.

5
00:00:53,006 --> 00:00:57,290
But if we stop there, we shall all too easily forget what we have come to know.

6
00:00:57,811 --> 00:01:04,299
for understanding a mental activity must be reinforced by actual experience.

7
00:01:06,123 --> 00:01:14,915
That actual experience will never come if we don't do something, and we never do anything unless we intend to do it, unless we make an act of will.

8
00:01:15,917 --> 00:01:23,126
Making an act of will on the Noble Eightfold Path means to go against any manifestation of ignorance, of delusion.

9
00:01:24,641 --> 00:01:30,188
Ignorance manifests itself in action as greed and hatred, the other two unwholesome roots.

10
00:01:31,430 --> 00:01:37,379
If right understanding dispels ignorance, then right intention dispels greed and hatred.

11
00:01:38,620 --> 00:01:43,927
Once these roots are undermined, we begin to move out of those syndromes of pleasure-pain and guilt.

12
00:01:46,370 --> 00:01:51,257
This is no easy task, as anyone who has tried to get rid of an unwanted habit will testify.

13
00:01:51,929 --> 00:01:57,013
For all the understanding that tobacco and alcohol do to the body, does it stop people smoking and drinking?

14
00:01:57,814 --> 00:02:02,418
Does the knowledge of the ill health caused by the two drugs cause a sudden change in behavior?

15
00:02:02,780 --> 00:02:03,280
Not at all.

16
00:02:04,301 --> 00:02:11,608
No matter how deep their understanding is, the smoker and the drinker will keep on smoking and drinking until they make the intention to stop.

17
00:02:12,908 --> 00:02:14,570
Is just making the one intention enough?

18
00:02:14,931 --> 00:02:15,431
Not at all.

19
00:02:16,432 --> 00:02:20,637
The intention must be repeated again and again until the old habit has...

20
00:02:21,275 --> 00:02:21,895
been loosened.

21
00:02:23,818 --> 00:02:31,766
Anyone who's tried to give up a strong habit, no matter what it is, knows full well what the training is and how arduous it is.

22
00:02:32,747 --> 00:02:36,611
But the prize, the liberation from such habits, is sweet victory indeed.

23
00:02:38,794 --> 00:02:42,818
The Buddha gave a very clear discourse as to what right intention was.

24
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:46,302
At the time he was at one of his main monasteries.

25
00:02:46,722 --> 00:02:51,406
it had been built by one of the foremost lay people, a millionaire called Anathapindika.

26
00:02:52,287 --> 00:02:58,913
It was situated in a reportedly beautiful place called the Jeta Grove near the capital city of Kosala, Sarvati.

27
00:03:00,234 --> 00:03:12,825
The Buddha starts by telling his listeners, Before my enlightenment, while I was still a bodhisattva, one intent on becoming truly enlightened, these thoughts occurred to me.

28
00:03:14,026 --> 00:03:16,188
Whatever are thoughts of sense pleasure,

29
00:03:16,793 --> 00:03:24,203
Whatever our thoughts of ill-will and aversion, whatever our thoughts of harming, these thoughts I consider one type.

30
00:03:25,544 --> 00:03:38,480
And whatever our thoughts of renunciation, whatever our thoughts of non-ill-will and non-aversion, and whatever our thoughts of non-harming, harmlessness, these I consider another type.

31
00:03:39,540 --> 00:03:49,230
Here, the Buddha is defining wrong intention as comprising three types of thoughts, those to do with sense pleasure, those to do with ill will, and those to do with harming.

32
00:03:50,010 --> 00:03:58,599
Out of these three types of wrong intentional thinking, the states of mind associated with pleasure, pain, and guilt, comes all our suffering.

33
00:04:00,020 --> 00:04:04,705
The Buddha then goes on to make explicit what the unwholesome results of such thinking are.

34
00:04:06,326 --> 00:04:08,028
I understood it in this way.

35
00:04:08,582 --> 00:04:37,375
thoughts of sense pleasure arise in me but they lead to hurting myself they lead to hurting others they lead to hurting myself and others they obstruct intuitive wisdom they are associated with distress and they do not lead to nibbana he says exactly the same thing about ill will and harming so here we have clear reasons why we need to abandon and certainly not indulge in these three types of thinking

36
00:04:37,860 --> 00:04:43,449
Firstly, they are unwholesome and bring present and future unwholesome results both to ourselves and others.

37
00:04:44,971 --> 00:04:56,225
Secondly, they are hindrances to the faculty of wisdom that intuits nibbana, which means that our meditation practice will be undermined by such states of mind that arise from such intentions.

38
00:04:57,427 --> 00:05:04,257
And thirdly, they lead to distress, to the rounds of rebirth, samsara, and away from liberation, nibbana.

39
00:05:06,802 --> 00:05:13,211
What is also important to note here is that these understandings came to the Buddha before he was enlightened.

40
00:05:14,334 --> 00:05:25,992
I think there is a mistaken understanding that the Buddha practiced only meditational techniques before his enlightenment, but he obviously spent a considerable time in reflection in thinking about what he was doing and what was happening to him.

41
00:05:27,154 --> 00:05:33,584
In our daily lives as meditators, we also need to regularly think about what is wholesome and what is unwholesome.

42
00:05:34,375 --> 00:05:38,158
Right understanding tops the list of the Eightfold Noble Path.

43
00:05:41,083 --> 00:05:44,906
Now, the next step the Bodhisatta made was to counteract such thought.

44
00:05:46,149 --> 00:05:52,435
He made a statement as to the importance of a type of thinking we would call these days self-suggestion and positive thinking.

45
00:05:53,377 --> 00:06:01,586
And throughout the discourse, he reminds us of the labour involved in this, referring to himself as faring on diligently, ardently and resolutely.

46
00:06:02,949 --> 00:06:04,230
The Buddha goes on to say...

47
00:06:05,307 --> 00:06:09,331
according to whatever a meditator continually ponders and reflects on.

48
00:06:10,572 --> 00:06:14,196
So his mind, as a result, develops a leaning in that direction.

49
00:06:15,317 --> 00:06:19,221
In other words, the more I think about sense pleasure, the more I'll crave for it.

50
00:06:19,942 --> 00:06:26,028
Thoughts build up their own energy, their own momentum, and finally demand expression in some form of speech or action.

51
00:06:27,449 --> 00:06:32,935
If someone keeps passing a bank and entertains thoughts of robbing it, it won't be long before he puts pen to paper.

52
00:06:35,091 --> 00:06:36,954
The next step, the Buddha says, is this.

53
00:06:38,396 --> 00:06:45,004
If a meditator ponders and reflects a lot on thoughts of sense pleasure, they bring up thoughts of renunciation.

54
00:06:46,487 --> 00:06:51,913
The Buddha here is not saying that we should conjure up thoughts of delightful sense pleasure and then renounce them.

55
00:06:52,555 --> 00:06:53,795
No, he goes on.

56
00:06:55,257 --> 00:07:01,386
If meditators make much of the thought of sense pleasure, the mind inclines to thoughts of sense pleasure.

57
00:07:02,817 --> 00:07:10,627
What the Buddha wants us to do is to bring to mind those thoughts about how sense pleasure leads to suffering and away from liberation.

58
00:07:11,648 --> 00:07:20,999
When we counter our desire for sense pleasure with contemplation of their dangers, then it is that the feeling to rid ourselves of them, to renounce them, arises.

59
00:07:24,202 --> 00:07:27,086
This renunciation arises out of wisdom.

60
00:07:27,757 --> 00:07:37,552
It isn't a practice of sacrifice if by sacrifice we mean to give something up in order to get something else, such as, I give up my desire for a holiday to get a new car.

61
00:07:39,675 --> 00:07:49,932
A meditator renounces indulging in sense pleasures not because he wants to gain favours or advantages, but because of the realisation that such self-indulgence brings harmful results.

62
00:07:51,834 --> 00:07:55,521
The results of such an action are the opposite of indulgence.

63
00:07:55,973 --> 00:07:59,617
It does not lead to hurting others and oneself.

64
00:07:59,637 --> 00:08:02,098
It allows intuitive wisdom to flourish.

65
00:08:02,119 --> 00:08:05,362
It leads away from suffering and towards liberation, nirvana.

66
00:08:06,302 --> 00:08:16,913
But the Buddha adds, If during the night and the day I should ponder and reflect on this, then from that source I do not behold fear.

67
00:08:19,074 --> 00:08:21,997
Fear underlies all our sense desire.

68
00:08:22,771 --> 00:08:26,074
it is to do with that essential self-definition, self-attachment.

69
00:08:26,875 --> 00:08:30,139
Who am I if I can't indulge in pleasures of sex, wine and song?

70
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:36,225
Our attachment to pleasure, when undermined, causes us to feel anxious and fearful.

71
00:08:37,226 --> 00:08:49,200
What the Buddha is telling us is that renouncing our attachment to sense desire, the compulsions, the obsessions, the way we define ourselves by what we enjoy, we shall also free ourselves from anxiety and fear.

72
00:08:51,947 --> 00:08:54,291
We left poor Billy stealing comics and sweets.

73
00:08:55,131 --> 00:09:01,181
His desire for these things had become so great that he couldn't resist the temptation of an easy self-satisfaction.

74
00:09:01,981 --> 00:09:03,583
His obsession possessed his mind.

75
00:09:04,446 --> 00:09:06,928
It stopped him thinking clearly about what he was doing.

76
00:09:08,071 --> 00:09:12,076
He may have acted on sheer impulse and just took the comics and bag of sweets.

77
00:09:12,996 --> 00:09:16,982
Or he may have reflected upon it and simply pushed away any notion of being caught.

78
00:09:18,664 --> 00:09:21,229
Billy has now totally reformed, I'm happy to report.

79
00:09:22,052 --> 00:09:25,417
But that doesn't mean he no longer reads comics or eats sweets.

80
00:09:25,576 --> 00:09:26,037
Not at all.

81
00:09:27,099 --> 00:09:28,780
What he's got rid of is the compulsion.

82
00:09:29,561 --> 00:09:32,725
If the money's there, or somebody buys him a comic, he reads it.

83
00:09:32,924 --> 00:09:33,505
He enjoys it.

84
00:09:34,366 --> 00:09:36,109
If someone offers him a sweet, he eats it.

85
00:09:36,528 --> 00:09:37,370
He enjoys the taste.

86
00:09:38,230 --> 00:09:41,495
There's no more sorrow and frustration if he doesn't get sweets and comics.

87
00:09:42,475 --> 00:09:48,802
He hasn't built up a collection of comics that he puts under lock and key for fear, for anxiety, that they will be stolen.

88
00:09:49,677 --> 00:09:52,038
Billy's learnt to renounce sweets and comics.

89
00:09:52,860 --> 00:09:54,801
Mind you, Billy's 40 years old now.

90
00:09:55,782 --> 00:09:58,083
Well, as I said, it takes time to overcome these things.

91
00:10:01,086 --> 00:10:04,349
This is a very important point to grasp.

92
00:10:04,369 --> 00:10:12,316
People often interpret this teaching of the Buddha to renounce pleasure as meaning to live grey lives, a sort of lacklustre bread-and-water existence.

93
00:10:13,297 --> 00:10:19,481
But men is the time in the scripture when the Buddha delights in the world, and he seems to have particular delight in shrines.

94
00:10:20,203 --> 00:10:26,636
During the last year of his life, after collecting alms food, he asks Ananda to accompany him to the Capala shrine.

95
00:10:28,100 --> 00:10:41,166
How delightful a spot Ananda is Vesali, and how charming the Udana shrine, and the Gautamaka shrine, and the shrine of the seven mangoes, and the shrine of the many suns, and the Sarandada shrine, and the Capala shrine.

96
00:10:43,727 --> 00:10:49,614
It is not that the Buddha is asking us to be blind to the beauty of the world, but to see it from a particular angle.

97
00:10:49,714 --> 00:10:51,096
It's all passing, all transient.

98
00:10:52,197 --> 00:10:56,321
And when it comes to our pleasure, it's not me, not mine, not a permanent self.

99
00:10:57,442 --> 00:11:03,850
Renouncing all this, our attachment to the world as a place of pleasure-seeking, leads to liberation from that snare.

100
00:11:04,669 --> 00:11:08,453
It leads to peace of mind, fearlessness, and total release, nibbana.

101
00:11:09,615 --> 00:11:12,739
The Zen master says it in a characteristically direct way.

102
00:11:13,445 --> 00:11:14,546
When I'm hungry, I eat.

103
00:11:15,267 --> 00:11:16,748
When I'm tired, I sleep.

104
00:11:19,451 --> 00:11:29,961
This sublime equanimity and joy is something we must work towards, and not simply by renouncing sense desire, pleasure-seeking, but also by undermining our ill-will and harmfulness.

105
00:11:31,423 --> 00:11:37,090
It is pondering the effects of aversion that brings about a disengagement, a non-aversion, a non-ill-will.

106
00:11:37,745 --> 00:11:46,219
It is by pondering the effects of harmfulness that brings about a refusal to act in a way that causes suffering to others or ourselves, a harmlessness.

107
00:11:47,880 --> 00:11:53,971
Perhaps we should spend some time every day sitting alone, going over what it means to hate, to actually cause harm.

108
00:11:55,453 --> 00:12:04,207
When we experience both of these in our daily lives, not simply as doers but as victims, when we meditate and experience what such thoughts are doing to us internally,

109
00:12:05,419 --> 00:12:24,845
When we see how they cloud the little wisdom we have, when we see how easily we seem to be absorbed into negativity and lose all balance and tranquility, when we see how it causes all this suffering and how it leads to more and more suffering, thoughts of escape naturally arise.

110
00:12:25,785 --> 00:12:29,410
Attitudes of non-aversion, non-harmfulness naturally develop.

111
00:12:31,854 --> 00:12:33,216
In the meditation especially,

112
00:12:33,549 --> 00:12:38,076
we come to know the power of our minds to reinforce their own conditioning.

113
00:12:39,158 --> 00:12:47,308
This very inbuilt mechanism of the mind to recondition existing states of mind is going to be the hardest task for us to use in our favor.

114
00:12:49,250 --> 00:13:03,269
Whenever we allow the mind to fantasize, be it on the bus, while driving, while having a cup of tea, whatever, every time it happens, it is reinforcing that respective habit, developing that negative conditioning, increasing our sankhara.

115
00:13:04,515 --> 00:13:06,919
In this discourse, the Buddha makes this plain.

116
00:13:08,341 --> 00:13:14,792
Whatever a meditator ponders and reflects upon, his mind, as a result, develops a bias in that way.

117
00:13:17,075 --> 00:13:23,765
Our efforts, therefore, in daily life and in meditation, must be to raise the energy to remain vigilant and alert.

118
00:13:24,486 --> 00:13:27,672
And as soon as such thoughts and fantasies come, we have to zap them.

119
00:13:28,032 --> 00:13:28,933
Aha, greed!

120
00:13:29,455 --> 00:13:30,876
Aha, the old grudge!

121
00:13:30,897 --> 00:13:32,919
Aha, my good friend's sweet revenge!

122
00:13:33,962 --> 00:13:39,691
then to reflect, to ponder, how if we had developed such thinking, what suffering it would have led to.

123
00:13:40,993 --> 00:13:45,740
The Buddha is so clear on this teaching, and these thoughts came to him before his enlightenment.

124
00:13:48,504 --> 00:13:53,850
At this point, something very wonderful happens, and I've tried to put it in diagrammatic form.

125
00:13:55,072 --> 00:13:57,836
We have now reached a stage of renouncing pleasure-seeking.

126
00:13:58,938 --> 00:14:03,345
The more we renounce, the more possessions cease to possess us,

127
00:14:04,152 --> 00:14:06,836
They simply become objects in our care for our use.

128
00:14:07,937 --> 00:14:11,722
We see them no longer as mine, but simply as objects that help us do things.

129
00:14:12,605 --> 00:14:14,908
We stop defining them as belonging to me.

130
00:14:15,850 --> 00:14:20,355
When I see another needs the use of that object, I let her or him use it.

131
00:14:21,177 --> 00:14:21,778
I don't need it.

132
00:14:22,720 --> 00:14:25,203
I might even let her have it.

133
00:14:26,385 --> 00:14:29,990
Renunciation naturally leads to generosity.

134
00:14:33,042 --> 00:14:34,703
Just think of your most precious object.

135
00:14:35,384 --> 00:14:39,128
Maybe it's a ring, a jewel, a video, a record, a car, whatever.

136
00:14:39,828 --> 00:14:42,510
You can test your enunciation, your non-attachment to it.

137
00:14:43,351 --> 00:14:47,495
You can test your generosity by allowing another to use it, even own it.

138
00:14:48,397 --> 00:14:50,578
Then observe closely the agitation of the mind.

139
00:14:51,919 --> 00:14:54,503
Someone happens to say, ''My video's broken.''

140
00:14:55,344 --> 00:14:58,326
Do we immediately say, ''Use mine?''

141
00:14:58,346 --> 00:15:00,889
Or do we go very quiet and look aimlessly out of the window?''

142
00:15:02,100 --> 00:15:08,107
Someone happens to say they'd love to make a trip, perhaps to see someone, but it's very difficult without a car.

143
00:15:08,128 --> 00:15:09,450
Do we say, use mine?

144
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:10,390
I insist.

145
00:15:11,172 --> 00:15:14,235
Or do we shrivel up in a paroxysm of fear in case they ask us?

146
00:15:16,238 --> 00:15:19,441
Do we check our monthly bank account and delight at the extra ten pounds?

147
00:15:20,261 --> 00:15:22,705
Does the thought arise, what cause can I support?

148
00:15:23,225 --> 00:15:24,707
Who might need this money more than me?

149
00:15:25,769 --> 00:15:28,412
Or do we fantasise on updating yet another possession?

150
00:15:32,375 --> 00:15:39,140
When we observe our minds like this, it comes as no surprise to see how closed in, how isolated, how small-minded some people can be.

151
00:15:40,101 --> 00:15:41,423
Selfishness diminishes us.

152
00:15:42,303 --> 00:15:44,206
Generosity is infinite expansion.

153
00:15:45,548 --> 00:15:51,133
Is it that impossible to have societies in which personally owned property, apart from personal effects, exist?

154
00:15:52,254 --> 00:15:56,057
The Buddha wanted his monks and nuns to come as close as possible to that ideal.

155
00:15:57,658 --> 00:16:00,761
A monk owns eight objects which he can justly call mine.

156
00:16:01,163 --> 00:16:04,587
and even here there are warnings not to take pride in such things.

157
00:16:04,607 --> 00:16:11,379
They have three robes, the begging bowl, thread to mend, a water strainer, a razor and a sitting mat.

158
00:16:12,760 --> 00:16:19,250
Apart from a few other things that can be owned on occasion, all the property in the monastery is owned by the establishment, the Sangha.

159
00:16:21,254 --> 00:16:27,322
It would be possible for lay communities to have a high degree of shared property, but it will never come by enforcement.

160
00:16:28,248 --> 00:16:32,854
Enforced collectives or cooperatives are undermined by the greed and jealousy of the members.

161
00:16:33,855 --> 00:16:38,360
Where there is greed and selfishness, how can there be non-attachment, sharing and generosity?

162
00:16:39,623 --> 00:16:43,668
The Buddha's understandings do not arise from a materialistic ideology.

163
00:16:44,710 --> 00:16:49,556
The Buddha's path has as its ideal, its goal, something beyond sense pleasure.

164
00:16:51,077 --> 00:16:56,144
It is only when the search for happiness in sense pleasure ceases, the great renunciation,

165
00:16:56,918 --> 00:16:58,581
that a sharing society will arise.

166
00:16:59,543 --> 00:17:00,183
It is possible.

167
00:17:03,570 --> 00:17:05,834
Now, a similar experience is found with ill-will.

168
00:17:06,976 --> 00:17:16,151
Reflecting on all our dislikes and feelings of aversion, we move to the middle ground of not entertaining such thoughts, not giving them any importance.

169
00:17:17,534 --> 00:17:20,479
This is a very important position to be able to take.

170
00:17:20,711 --> 00:17:24,537
if we really want to undermine our hatreds, angers and frustrations.

171
00:17:25,258 --> 00:17:29,503
If, for instance, we dislike someone, we need to ponder the consequences of such an action.

172
00:17:31,185 --> 00:17:38,395
We need to realise it is only an attitude, and we don't have to obey it, say it's right, it's me, identify with it.

173
00:17:39,176 --> 00:17:45,826
Within ourselves, we need to take up a position of, all right, I don't like that person, but I'm not going to do anything about it.

174
00:17:46,686 --> 00:17:50,652
No one's perfect, and what's the point of being angry over another's faults?

175
00:17:51,204 --> 00:17:51,885
How does it help?

176
00:17:52,487 --> 00:17:56,053
In fact, I'm going to try and see her or him in a more positive light.

177
00:17:57,394 --> 00:18:06,249
One begins to see the positive attributes of the person, and this is where non-ill will becomes good will, loving kindness.

178
00:18:08,010 --> 00:18:15,303
So with harmfulness, actually translating thoughts of ill will into action is harmfulness.

179
00:18:15,323 --> 00:18:16,825
There's a lot of pleasure in it.

180
00:18:17,023 --> 00:18:17,925
Sweet revenge.

181
00:18:18,626 --> 00:18:20,871
Watching one's enemy, one's rival squirm.

182
00:18:21,692 --> 00:18:23,675
The feelings of victory with the cutting word.

183
00:18:24,457 --> 00:18:25,839
Why else do it but for the pleasure?

184
00:18:27,102 --> 00:18:32,612
It's hard for ordinary people to understand, but torturers get job satisfaction.

185
00:18:34,515 --> 00:18:41,326
Pondering on the karmic consequences of harming others is often enough to reach a position of no harm, harmlessness.

186
00:18:42,741 --> 00:18:52,849
When we actually do harm in our thoughts to ourselves, in speech or actions to ourselves and others, it is transgressing the moral law and starting up the reactions associated with guilt.

187
00:18:52,869 --> 00:18:59,455
When we undermine this tendency within us, there arises in us an abhorrence of cruelty and a desire to help others.

188
00:18:59,955 --> 00:19:03,839
In this way, harmlessness transforms into compassion.

189
00:19:05,721 --> 00:19:08,544
So now we have completed our spiral out of suffering.

190
00:19:09,324 --> 00:19:12,646
The more we are ensnared in the syndromes of pleasure, pain and guilt,

191
00:19:13,268 --> 00:19:15,511
the more we are being overcome with delusion.

192
00:19:16,653 --> 00:19:18,056
The more our ignorance is growing.

193
00:19:19,277 --> 00:19:26,048
The greatest delusion lies in the fact that as the selfishness increases, so does our idea of self-importance increase.

194
00:19:27,170 --> 00:19:28,792
Our ego gets bigger all the time.

195
00:19:29,894 --> 00:19:41,132
As we spend more and more time feeding this pride, this ego-centeredness, the more we are cutting off the world as people are turned away by our lack of generosity, sympathy, care for others and so on.

196
00:19:41,804 --> 00:19:47,789
How can the enlarged ego give to others when it is so involved in giving to itself?

197
00:19:47,809 --> 00:19:53,375
As selfish persons think they are growing more important, the less important do other people think they are.

198
00:19:54,477 --> 00:19:58,441
Life moves towards isolation, loneliness, mental sickness, to hell.

199
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:00,482
What is hell but a state of mind?

200
00:20:01,364 --> 00:20:08,631
As my favourite poet, General Manly Hopkins says, I see the lost are like this, and they're scourged to be as I am mine.

201
00:20:09,010 --> 00:20:11,794
They're sweating selves, but worse.

202
00:20:15,384 --> 00:20:20,594
To escape this downward spiral, this disappearance into the world of the little mind, demands hard training.

203
00:20:21,454 --> 00:20:23,198
It's arduous work and full of pain.

204
00:20:23,238 --> 00:20:27,424
There are many setbacks and times when advance seems to elude the meditator.

205
00:20:28,446 --> 00:20:31,912
Sometimes we even think we're getting worse for all the meditation and attempts at awareness.

206
00:20:33,094 --> 00:20:36,680
Letting go of our desires and obsessions fills us with acute discomfort.

207
00:20:37,582 --> 00:20:39,704
We so much want, desire, crave.

208
00:20:40,681 --> 00:20:49,634
Letting go of aversions makes us feel them even more keenly within ourselves, since now we are no longer displacing these feelings onto others by angry attacks and so on.

209
00:20:50,255 --> 00:20:51,877
We feel them burning inside us.

210
00:20:53,220 --> 00:21:02,554
Our actions of harmfulness in thought, speech and action scorch us with shame or freezes us with fear as we face up to the consequences we now no longer shrug off.

211
00:21:03,731 --> 00:21:16,951
But just as a rocket escapes the gravitational pull of the earth through the tremendous power of its own boosters, so we can pull ourselves free of the gravitational pull of our negative conditionings by our own power of resolute determination.

212
00:21:17,951 --> 00:21:19,413
No easy task.

213
00:21:19,433 --> 00:21:22,858
And the Buddha is the first to tell us it was no easy task for him either.

214
00:21:23,800 --> 00:21:26,203
Diligent, ardent and self-resolute.

215
00:21:26,744 --> 00:21:28,186
That's how he describes himself.

216
00:21:29,939 --> 00:21:37,730
Now as we do begin to pull further and further away, the more we begin to experience moments of light-heartedness, of mental poise, tranquility.

217
00:21:38,530 --> 00:21:42,776
How easy it is to be generous, loving and compassionate when we're like that.

218
00:21:44,038 --> 00:21:46,280
Slowly the training becomes more and more joyous.

219
00:21:47,142 --> 00:21:50,166
When we are truly generous and we give, joy arises.

220
00:21:51,028 --> 00:21:52,970
When we truly love, we love with joy.

221
00:21:54,031 --> 00:21:57,836
When compassion arises and we help, joy is the fruit of our labour.

222
00:21:58,828 --> 00:22:08,660
Throughout our whole training lives we shall move in and out of these states, one time generous, sometimes stingy, sometimes loving, other times not caring, and so on.

223
00:22:08,680 --> 00:22:21,493
But if our training is ardent and resolute and diligent, the movement will be upward and outward, spiraling even to the point where generosity, love and compassion are habitual, to the point of wholesome, spontaneous action.

224
00:22:22,454 --> 00:22:28,801
This is one of the attributes of the Buddha, Vidyacaranasampanno, endowed with knowledge and virtue,

225
00:22:29,321 --> 00:22:33,586
There was no separation between what he knew to be right and how he behaved.

226
00:22:34,188 --> 00:22:35,329
What he said, he did.

227
00:22:38,113 --> 00:22:39,955
The role of meditation here is twofold.

228
00:22:40,757 --> 00:22:45,742
It puts us directly in touch with our states of mind and it allows the negative states to die out.

229
00:22:46,884 --> 00:22:57,337
Throughout our daily life we maintain a bright alertness with intentions switched to generosity, loving kindness and compassion so that all day our actions are motivated from that base.

230
00:23:00,777 --> 00:23:05,300
When the mind is in any of these three modes, the root of wrong action is destroyed.

231
00:23:06,301 --> 00:23:09,365
Where there was ignorance, there is now its opposite, wisdom.

232
00:23:10,487 --> 00:23:15,351
When wisdom is put into action, the other two roots of greed and hatred are destroyed.

233
00:23:16,112 --> 00:23:20,797
Where there was greed and hatred, there is now generosity, love and compassion.

234
00:23:21,457 --> 00:23:22,458
That's wisdom in action.

235
00:23:23,980 --> 00:23:29,265
When we are moving from the base of wisdom, the intuitive faculty is empowered, it is free,

236
00:23:29,953 --> 00:23:36,007
That's why it is in ordinary daily life that so many of the enlightening and spiritual experiences are had.

237
00:23:36,728 --> 00:23:39,534
You can experience nibbana while peeling a banana.

238
00:23:42,240 --> 00:23:44,284
Most of the discourses end with a simile.

239
00:23:44,855 --> 00:24:04,392
In this discourse of the two types of thinking, the Buddha likens himself to a man who leads a herd of deer out of the marshy ground of sense pleasure, along a secure road of the Eightfold Noble Path, past the male decoy of passion and the female lure of delusion, finally leading to the open space of liberation.

240
00:24:06,213 --> 00:24:10,738
At the end of the discourse on the twofold types of thinking, the Buddha encourages us.

241
00:24:12,459 --> 00:24:13,140
Meditate.

242
00:24:13,761 --> 00:24:16,286
Do not be lazy and feel sorry later on.

243
00:24:17,028 --> 00:24:18,569
This is my instruction to you.

244
00:24:19,893 --> 00:24:25,321
Thus spoke the Lord, delighted the monks and lay people, rejoiced in what had been said.

245
00:24:28,647 --> 00:24:30,730
Well, I hope this talk has been interesting and helpful.

246
00:24:31,553 --> 00:24:33,415
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

247
00:24:34,116 --> 00:24:37,001
May all of you attain an Ibanic peace within.

